<FIRST>u i AM-BoyPilot 1stLd-Writethru a0675 06-18 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boy Pilot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede: REYKJAVIK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Boy Pilot Lands in Oslo after Crossing Vast and Frigid Ocean ^Eds:
Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with landing in Norway. Pickup 11th graf `Tony,
from...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old American pilot who hopes to
become the youngest person to fly around the world landed his small
Cessna 210 Centurion Sunday after flying across the icy North
Atlantic.
   ``It was like flying over a big lake,'' said Tony Aliengena after
the nearly six-hour flight over the often storm-swept 1,100 miles of
ocean, probably the longest, most treacherous leg of the flight.
   Tony landed his single-engine turboprop Cessna in Oslo late
Sunday, about 10 minutes after an escort plane carrying his mother,
sister and Soviet and American journalists.
   The boy and his family planned to rest and sightsee in Norway's
capital city before flying to Sweden on Monday on a trip dubbed
Friendship Flight 89.
   Tony, from San Juan Capistrano, Calif., is carrying letters from
American schoolchildren to Soviet schoolchildren and an 800-foot
``friendship scroll'' signed by 200,000 American youngsters. He
plans to present the scroll to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev when
he reaches Moscow.
   Tony set out June 5 from John Wayne Airport at Costa Mesa,
Calif., on the 19,000-mile trip dubbed Friendship Flight '89.
</TEXT>
