<FIRST>r i AM-IndianLeader     06-18 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Leader,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Court Rules Satiacum Is Not A Political Refugee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian court has ruled
that a former Puyallup tribal leader convicted of racketeering in
the United States is not a political refugee under Canadian law.
   The unanimous ruling by the Canadian Federal Court of Appeals
could lead to Robert Satiacum's deportation to the United States,
the Morning News Tribune of Tacoma reported in Sunday's editions.
   The court held that Canada's immigration appeals board
incorrectly granted Satiacum's request to become Canada's first
political refugee from the United States.
   The immigration board had agreed with Satiacum's claim that he
was in danger of persecution and death if he returned to America.
However, that decision was appealed by the Canadian Department of
Education and Immigration, which said Satiacum sought refuge in
Canada to escape a prison term in the United States.
   The case will return to the immigration appeals board, but that
board is precluded from deciding in Satiacum's favor a second time.
   Once the board rules again, Satiacum's case will return to a
hearing to decide whether he will be deported to the United States.
   Satiacum, a resident of Tacoma, Wash., went to Canada following
conviction on 46 counts of racketeering in November 1982. After he
fled, Satiacum was convicted of 24 counts of embezzlement. He was
not sentenced in either case.
   Satiacum, meanwhile, faces criminal charges in British Columbia
that could jeopardize his efforts to win a permanent home in Canada.
   He is to go on trial Nov. 6 on charges that he molested a young
girl. Under Canadian law, a conviction on the charge _ which carries
a 10-year prison sentence _ would give the immigration minister the
right to deport him without a hearing.
   Neither Satiacum nor his lawyer, David Gibbons, could be reached
for comment Friday.
</TEXT>
