<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Monticciolo     06-18 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Monticciolo,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Former Regional HUD Director Works at HUD Contractor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Embargoed until 5 a.m.; time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former regional director of the Department of
Housing and Urban Development received a $125,000-a-year job from
businessmen who shared in a $17 million profit from a government
contract the official helped to award, New York Newsday reported in
its Sunday editions.
   Joseph Monticciolo left his government job early in 1988 to
become board chairman and chief executive of the Eagle Capital
Group, an investment group headed by developer Sheldon Goldstein.
   Also Sunday, The New York Times reported that more than half the
money New York state received from a special discretionary HUD fund
went to projects pushed by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
   Newsday reported that most members of the Eagle group also were
involved in an investment group headed by Goldstein that made a
large profit on at least one deal.
   Goldstein is a prominent financial supporter of Gov. Mario Cuomo
and D'Amato.
   The investment group bought seven housing projects from HUD in
1983 for $10.9 million after putting up only $550,000 in cash. Three
years later, the group sold the projects for an estimated $17
million profit, the paper said.
   While Monticciolo was regional director, several other HUD
management contracts were awarded to Goldstein firms, the newspaper
said.
   The Eagle Capital Group was formed late in 1987, one month before
Monticciolo left HUD. He receives $125,000 a year to direct the
firm. He also has received a 15 percent share of the group at almost
no cost. Other partners invested a total of $1 million in the firm.
   Newsday reported that both Eagle and Monticciolo are being
investigated by Congress as part of a growing probe by Congress into
political favoritism at HUD during the Reagan administration.
   Neither Monticciolo nor Goldstein would comment on the story, the
newspaper said.
   A spokesman for Eagle said Monticciolo had not favored Goldstein
while at HUD and had done nothing wrong in the housing projects deal.
   Meanwhile, the Times reported that almost a third of the nearly
$38 million in a HUD discretionary fund went to projects in New York
state between 1981 and 1988. The funds were at the department
secretary's disposal.
   More than half of the $12 million the state got went to projects
supported by D'Amato, the Times said.
   None of the projects is known to be part of the federal
investigation into HUD, the paper said.
   A swimming pool for Island Park, D'Amato's hometown, has been
criticized as an unnecessary HUD-financed project. But the Times
said most of the projects pushed by D'Amato appeared to be
legitimate.
</TEXT>
