<FIRST>r a AM-PowerExplosion     06-18 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Power Explosion,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underground Explosion Causes Power Outage in Omaha, Neb.; Three Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people on fire crawled out of an
underground utility switching vault and a third had to be carried
out after an explosion that knocked out power in much of downtown
Omaha Saturday night, witnesses said.
   One of the victims, a female worker for the Omaha Public Power
District, yelled ``Help me. Help me. I'm on fire,'' said Kari
Eckert, a security guard for the telephone company, who was one of
the first people on the scene.
   ``I turned around and I almost got sick,'' Ms. Eckert said. ``I
was scared to death.''
   Two of the victims got out of the vault and were in an alley and
the third had to be carried out, she said.
   Dan Shields used his coat to try to beat flames off one of two
men who were injured. ``Their clothes were burnt completely off. It
was sickening,'' he said.
   The three victims were utility employees, said Omaha Police Sgt.
Robert Frock. He said the explosion's cause was not immediately
known.
   The crew was working on a project for the phone company,
replacing a switching unit, said Jim Brader, a US West
Communications spokesman. He said he did not know how much
electricity was running through the lines at the time of the
explosion.
   A man and a woman were taken to St. Joseph's Hospital, where they
were in critical condition, with second- and third-degree burns over
80 percent of their bodies, Frock said.
   Another man was taken to the University of Nebraska Medical
Center, where he was listed in critical conditon. He was to be
transferred to a burn unit at a hospital in Lincoln, the medical
center said.
   The explosion knocked out seven electrical circuits in the
downtown area, said Mark Gautier Jr., an Omaha Public Power District
spokesman. The power was expected to remain off until early Sunday.
   Some minor traffic accidents were reported in downtown Omaha
because several traffic lights were out.
</TEXT>
