<FIRST>r i BC-Poland-Election     06-18 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Election,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists, Solidarity in Runoff of Historic Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poles voted again Sunday as the
Solidarity-led opposition tried to capture the few open
parliamentary seats it did not clinch in the first round of the
freest elections in Eastern Europe in four decades.
   The communist party hoped to soften the stunning rebuff of the
June 4 voting. The independent Solidarity union won 252 of the 261
seats open to it in the new National Assembly.
   The turnout of the 27 million eligible voters remained a big
question for Sunday's second round. Many said they made their views
clear in the first round and turned their attention back to the
economic difficulties of daily life in Poland.
   All but nine of the 303 elections were being contested only by
communist candidates and their allies who failed to get first-round
majorities.
   However, Solidarity sought to bolster its power in the National
Assembly by endorsing the most reform-oriented party members in the
runoff.
   Eight seats remained undecided in the new, freely elected
100-member Senate, where Solidarity candidates took 92 places by
getting more than 50 percent of the vote on June 4.
   Solidarity also won 160 of the 161 seats open to independent
candidates in the 460-member Sejm, or parliament, during the first
round.
   Only three Sejm candidates from the communist party coalition _
reformers who had gained support from Solidarity activists in their
regions _ won first-round victories.
   In addition, 33 of the 35 top government officials on the
``national list'' of unopposed Sejm candidates did not receive the
required 50 percent of the votes cast, and they have been replaced
by 66 new candidates for the second round.
   The communists' best chance of winning a Senate seat was Henryk
Stoklosa, a rich fertilizer company owner from the western province
of Pila. He was the only coalition candidate to outpoll a Solidarity
opponent, although he did not get a majority.
   The elections are part of political and economic reforms
negotiated during two months of unprecedented talks between the
communist government and the opposition. The two sides also agreed
in April to make Solidarity legal again.
</TEXT>
