<FIRST>u i BC-PlaneCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0631 06-18 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Plane Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0631,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Afghan Airliner Crashes In Iran After Gunmen Struggle With Pilot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 26 survivors, plane Soviet-built,
36 passengers aboard, probably 5-6 crew members. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan airliner crashed in Iran on
Sunday after gunmen tried to seize the plane and struggled with the
pilot, the official Iranian news agency said. Twenty-six people
reportedly survived the crash.
   The Soviet-built Antonov An-26 airliner went down near Zabol, a
city in eastern Iran close to the rugged Afghan border, the Islamic
Republic News Agency said. IRNA said initial reports indicate that
36 passengers were aboard the 40-seat, short-haul aircraft. The
civilian version of the plane, originally designed as a military
transport, normally carries a crew of five or six.
   The agency said it was not known how many casualties there were.
   The report, monitored in Nicosia, did not identify the gunmen,
say how many there were, or provide any other details on the
attempted hijacking.
   IRNA said the plane crashed at 12:30 p.m. and that Iranian rescue
teams were immediately ordered to the scene in Sistan-Baluchestan
province.
   The agency said Prime Minister Hussein Musavi sent his deputy
premier for political affairs, Alireza Moayyeri, to Zabol to
investigate the incident.
   It quoted Moayyeri as saying before he left Tehran, 700 miles
northwest of Zabol, that 26 people, including pilot Mirvis Paktia,
were dragged from the wreckage and hospitalized in Zabol. The
pilot's condition was not given.
   The news agency quoted several survivors as saying the aircraft
crashed after the pilot struggled with the unidentified hijackers.
``He lost control of the plane, and that led to its crash,'' the
agency said.
   It was not immediately known where the airliner was flying from
or its destination. But it was apparently on an internal Afghan
flight.
   Moayyeri declined further comment on the incident ``until the
matter has been fully investigated,'' IRNA reported.
   Iran supported the Moslem guerrillas who fought the Soviet army
in Afghanistan for nine years until it withdrew earlier this year.
Tehran continues to support the guerrillas' war against Kabul's
Marxist government.
</TEXT>
