<DOCNO> AP890618-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Flood     06-18 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Flood,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain-swollen River Floods 10 Villages; Hundreds Marooned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOOSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rain-swollen river burst through an
embankment in eastern Bangladesh, sending rushing waters through 10
villages and leaving hundreds of people marooned on rooftops,
officials said Sunday.
   At least 600 people climbed on top of their homes to escape the
surging waters of the River Gumti, which tore a 100-foot-wide hole
in the embankment at Debidar village on Saturday, officials at the
Flood Forecasting Center said.
   The river, fed by incessant rains and a swollen Brahmaputra River
that feeds it, flooded Debidar and nine other villages in Comilla
district, 55 miles east of Dhaka, said an official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   He said more than 500 people had fled their homes in panic and
taken shelter in a school.
   Rescue workers were trying to close the breach and remove the
marooned people from the roofs, he said.
   The Flood Forecasting Center said other tributaries of the
Brahmaputra and Ganges, which crisscross Bangladesh, were steadily
rising. At least 10 areas in northern and eastern Bangladesh were
likely to be inundated by Monday if the rivers continued to rise,
the center said.
   The two rivers originate in neigboring India. The Brahmaputra
passes through the eastern Indian state of Assam before flowing
through Bangladesh into the Bay of Bengal.
   Officials in Bangladesh said the flood destroyed about 15,000
acres of paddy, the main food crop of the impoverished nation.
   Bangladesh, a low lying delta of 110 million people, alternates
between floods and drought. Two months ago, a drought destroyed
almost half the 5 million tons of paddy that was ready for harvest.
   Last year, three fourths of the country was inundated during
floods that killed at least 1,400 people and left 2.3 million
homeless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
