<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Island     06-18 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Island,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Arriving in Hong Kong Towed to Deserted Island</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Boat People, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAI A CHAU, HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese boat people arriving in
Hong Kong braved the seas hoping for resettlement in the West, but
instead they are finding themselves towed to this deserted island.
   Tents raised by sticks and branches are their homes. Worn-out
mats, cardboard and plastic sheets are their beds. Daily meals are
biscuits and canned food.
   Litter is spead over the island's tiny paths and slopes, its
stench worsened by the summer heat. There is no electricity.
   About 4,500 Vietnamese were on the island during a
government-arranged visit by reporters Friday.
   ``My future is bleak,'' said 30-year-old Phan Quyen, a dental
technician who fled Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon. ``I want to
go to Australia. Anywhere is better than Tai A Chau. Life here is
tough, I have not had any rice for 11 days.''
   Le Thi Chau, 31, an English teacher from Danang in central
Vietnam said: ``I never imagined it like this. It's terrible. But I
have sympathy with the Hong Kong government. Many, many people have
arrived.''
   There are no cooking facilities on the island and refugees are
forced to dig holes for toilets, said Marine Police chief inspector
Au Wai-lam.
   ``There is no hygiene at all,'' he said. ``I feel sorry for them,
but look at the situation in Hong Kong. We just can't cope with it.''
   A junior officer said the boat people often fight over food and
space. People from northern Vietnam clash with the southern
Vietnamese, others said.
   Since May 30, authorities have been towing boats carrying
Vietnamese to the island, 19 miles from the city center, because no
other facilities remain in Hong Kong. Initially, the refugees were
allowed ashore only to relieve themselves.
   The Vietnamese spend several days on the island before being
moved to facilities in Hong Kong.
   Western relief agencies have criticized conditions at Tai A Chau.
   When Typhoon Dot approached earlier this month, authorities moved
some of the Vietnamese from Tai A Chau to a nearby island and others
to the Marine Police headquarters on the main Hong Kong island. When
the threat subsided, they were moved back.
   Besides the Vietnamese, the only people on the island are Chow
Yu-fook and Ng Sing-tai, an elderly Chinese couple who live near the
pier. They say the Vietnamese have ruined their peaceful existence.
   ``I can't sleep at night,'' said Mrs. Chow, 62. ``They are
annoying. The beans and sweet potatoes I grew are gone. I can't even
pick up shells. The fish are all scared away by the boats.''
</TEXT>
