<DOCNO> AP890618-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietChildren     06-18 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Children,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Children, `The Only Privileged Class,' Neglected by System, Writer
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM HEINTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets had comforted themselves with the belief
their children would have better lives, but glasnost is making them
painfully aware of how untrue that can be, a Soviet journalist says.
   ``There was an expression that `children are the only privileged
class,''' said Natalie Darialova. That belief was easy to maintain
during the decades when officials denied social problems and branded
acknowledgment as undermining communism.
   But under the recent policies of glasnost, or more openness,
Soviets are finding that the system has failed the children, leaving
them neglected at home or stupefied with boredom, she said.
   An estimated 300,000 are consigned to orphanages that do little
more than feed and clothe them, Ms. Darialova said.
   The root of those abuses was the top-heavy bureaucracy and the
corruption that flourished during Leonid Brezhnev's years as Soviet
leader, she said in a recent interview here while on a private trip.
   In addition, she said, society's pressure on women to work _ and
their need for the extra income _ led many couples to neglect their
children. A prominent Soviet sociologist reported last year that 94
percent of Soviet women worked and that working mothers spent an
average of just 30 minutes a week ``on spiritual communication with
their children.''
   Ms. Darialova began investigating the problems of youth in 1985
when she was assigned by the weekly Literary Gazette to do a story
about five children left unattended who died in a house fire.
   When she asked local authorities why the parents hadn't been able
to find someone to watch the children, ``I found that no one was in
charge'' of child welfare, she said. ``The local soviets (councils)
had no authority, no money. They were the poorest bodies.
   ``Under Brezhnev, social and cultural programs were cut. Much
money went to who knows where,'' she said.
   The bleakness of life in many Soviet cities is, in effect, a sort
of child abuse, Ms. Darialova said. Many children have little to do
with their free time and youthful energy.
   That can lead to street crime, which Soviet figures say has risen
by about 40 percent in the past year, or other anti-social behavior.
One press report bemoaned motorcycle gangs made up of ``minors who
like to ride with the wind.''
   ``Imagine a city with no cultural facilities. Children can go out
and buy a bottle of wine, and the road to crime is open,'' she said,
adding that by ``cultural facilities'' she meant movies and places
for rock music, as well as opera and classical music.
   The government has begun an extensive program to combat alcohol
abuse by upping prices and raising the drinking age to 21, but it
has not reduced children's desire to combat boredom through
intoxication, she said.
   Coming to grips with their children's problems has been traumatic
because ``in general, there is much love. All their lives is in
their children ... Russian babushkas (grandmothers) are famous for
their devotion.
   ``In discussions I often hear that in Brezhnev's time we didn't
have these problems. Of course it is frightening when you open a
newspaper and it's more and more (problems).
   ``But it is a new atmosphere. We now feel the ability to do
something, not to be just obedient employees.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
