<FIRST>r a AM-DefiningDixie Bjt   06-18 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defining Dixie, Bjt,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Gala to Herald Release of Encyclopedia of Southern Culture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can be doggone sure Dixie ain't like
other parts of this here United States. That's the message of a work
scrunching the South's A-to-Z uniqueness into an 8-pound, 1,643-page
book to be unveiled this week.
   Beginning with baseball great Hank Aaron and ending with zydeco,
``wonderful Cajun music played with an accordion,'' editor Bill
Ferris says the newly published Encyclopedia of Southern Culture
provides a one-of-a-kind single-volume reference work.
   The book boils down the region to its bare bones, he says, but
leaves the marrow of the South's contributions and history in 24
major subjects _ including agriculture, art and literature, black
life, law, politics and science.
   Articles focus on every aspect of Southern life from defining
``good ole boys and girls,'' to how to prepare collard greens and
okra, to explaining the impact air conditioning has had on the
region's economic development.
   ``Roots'' author Alex Haley wrote the forward to the
encyclopedia, which was edited by Ferris, director of the University
of Mississippi's Center for the Study of Southern Culture, and
Charles Wilson, professor of history and Southern studies at the
university. It is to be unveiled at a gala Tuesday in Washington.
   ``I testify that this Encyclopedia of Southern Culture mirrors
the very best of what has lately come to be called `the new
South,''' Haley wrote. ``Never before has such a volume been
produced by a team so committed to distilling and presenting our
Southern distinctiveness.''
   Ferris said Haley was asked to do the forward because ``we felt
his work really was symbolic of our quest to understand the roots of
all Southerners. And Alex Haley has become a spokesman for bridging
white and black, old and young, and male and female worlds _ which
this volume seeks to do.''
   The dinner Tuesday in the U.S. Senate Caucus Room will have as
its hosts the state's congressional delegation and University of
Mississippi Chancellor Gerald Turner. The chairman of the National
Endowment for the Humanities, Lynne Cheney, and Mississippi author
Willie Morris are among those scheduled to speak.
   Ferris said that between 600 and 800 are expected to attend.
   The encyclopedia, funded by more than $400,000 in public and
private grants including almost $246,000 from the National
Endowment, features articles by more than 800 experts on various
aspects of the South.
   Although most of the entries were written by academic scholars _
with ``academic jargon'' edited out, other contributors were
solicited, Ferris said.
   ``For example, the man who wrote the article on Mississippi River
law is a practicing lawyer in Vicksburg, Emmett Ward, whose law
practice is focused on the river,'' Ferris said.
   Cheney said she's pleased with the finished product. The $49.95
work printed by the University of North Carolina Press should be
widely distributed by fall.
   ``The Encyclopedia of Southern Culture masterfully illustrates
Southern religion and folk life, explores Southern manners and
myths, and celebrates Southern literature and art,'' Cheney said.
``Hundreds of dedicated scholars contributed to this work and
succeeded in capturing the unique richness of life in the South.''
</TEXT>
