<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Quake Bjt   06-18 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criminal Charges Brought Against Armenia Builders For Quake Damage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have begun prosecuting builders whose
shoddy work caused hundreds of new buildings to collapse during the
Armenian earthquake, killing thousands of people who would otherwise
have survived, a newspaper said Sunday.
   Workers used inferior materials, garbage and even an empty bucket
rather than solid concrete during construction of some buildings in
the Soviet republic, the newspaper Socialist Industry reported.
   The Dec. 7 quake killed an estimated 25,000 people and left
500,000 homeless.
   On Thursday, a government commission formed to probe the quality
of construction in the devastated earthquake zone gave prosecutors
the results of its investigation.
   ``Thousands of people could have survived the catastrophic
earthquake in Armenia if basic building standards and regulations
were observed,'' the commission concluded, Socialist Industry said.
   The prosecutor's office has begun criminal proceedings against
leaders of building organizations, work superintendents and
designers, V. Nenashev, deputy head of the prosecutor's
investigations office, told the newspaper.
   Those convicted of substandard construction and building code
violations face a maximum penalty of five years in prison.
   Construction in the Soviet Union is of notoriously poor quality
and subject to long delays and theft of materials.
   The commission's report on building practices in Armenia is
certain to have nationwide ramifications. The Soviet Union is in the
midst of a program to provide every family with individual housing
by the year 2000.
   Most of the buildings that collapsed in northwestern Armenia were
five- or nine-story apartment houses, which are common in the Soviet
Union.
   Immediately after the quake, Soviet officials including President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev said slipshod construction caused hundreds of
relatively new apartment buildings to tumble into ruins of concrete
bits and metal.
   ``Why did buildings from three years ago collapse while those
built with three or five stories under (former Soviet Premier Nikita
S.) Khrushchev are still standing?'' Gorbachev asked during a Dec.
11 visit to Spitak, the city hit hardest by the quake.
   Nenashev told Socialist Industry that a key junction of one house
where dozens of people were killed was filled with an empty bucket,
some sort of bars, and construction refuse. The junction should have
been a solid ``monolith'' of concrete, he said.
   A photograph accompanying the article showed the metal bucket
surrounded by rubble.
   Nenashev also discussed slipshod work discovered in the ruins of
one 20-apartment, five-story stone house built in 1985 in Spitak.
The strength of concrete in solid reinforced columns was up to three
times below required level, he said.
   Reporters visiting another devastated city, Leninakan, shortly
after the quake saw one broken slab from a collapsed building
marked, ``This piece of concrete is not to be used,'' indicating it
was below standard. The Soviet press has reported that much of the
concrete was more sand than cement and branded those responsible
``scrap builders.''
   Mortar used in masonry of inner and outer walls of the Spitak
house had no bond strength because it contained no cement, Nenashev
told the newspaper. Rigid horizontal floor disks required for
buildings in quake-prone areas were missing. Anti-seismic belts were
not reinforced and were not attached to non-supporting walls, he
said.
   Some Leninakan residents have said that up until 20 years ago, no
one built anything taller than two or three stories in the
earthquake-prone area.
   The government has launched a program to rebuild the devastated
area and promised that no buildings taller than three or four
stories will be put up there. The goal is to finish reconstruction
in two years.
   But a commission of the ruling Communist Party Politburo
complained Saturday that ``rates of restoration work are far from
satisfactory.'' It said customers and contractors are poorly
organized and that the reconstruction effort suffers from a shortage
of manpower, technical facilities, stone, cement and timber.
</TEXT>
