<SECOND>AM-South Korea-Boat People,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Refugees Burn Boat After Denied Permission to Land</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Boat People, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean patrol boats rescued 78
Vietnamese refugees who set their boat on fire and jumped into the
water after they were refused permission to land, a news agency said
Sunday.
   The patrol boats were escorting the refugee vessel out to
international waters when the 30-ton boat suddenly burst into flames
and sank, Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, quoted naval police
as saying.
   The incident happened Saturday off the southern island of Cheju,
Yonhap said.
   The 45 men and 33 women were ordered to stay aboard the patrol
boats, Yonhap said. It was not clear whether the government would
allow the boat people to settle in South Korea, which does not have
diplomatic relations with Vietnam.
   Naval authorities had ordered the Vietnamese to stay out of South
Korean waters after blocking a May 7 attempt by the boat people to
land on the western island of Uldo, the agency said.
   Hundreds of Vietnamese refugees have been allowed to stay in
South Korea or have gone to other countries through South Korean
refugee camps since 1975, when the Saigon government fell. Recently,
however, Seoul has been reluctant to accept refugees from communist
Vietnam.
