<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     06-18 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally to Support Chinese Dissidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people gathered Sunday to support
the pro-democracy movement in China and watch the unveiling of a
replica of the ``Goddess of Democracy,'' the statue torn down by
troops in Beijing.
   About 4,000 people attended the ceremony in Victoria Park. It was
the latest expression of this British colony's anger over the
crackdown by the Chinese government, which is to assume control of
Hong Kong in 1997.
   The 33-foot-high statue, an image of a torch-bearing woman that
was inspired by the Statue of Liberty, is a replica of the statue
put up by protesters in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   ``A statue was knocked down, but thousands will be erected all
over the world,'' said Szeto Wah, a lawmaker who presided over the
ceremony. ``There will be a day when the statue will be erected on
Tiananmen Square in Beijing.''
   Wah laid a wreath at an empty tomb beside the plastic statue. It
was inscribed: ``To the memory of compatriots who died or were
injured in the patriotic pro-democracy movement'' and ``Democracy
martyrs are eternal.''
   The crowd sang ``For Freedom,'' a song Hong Kong activists wrote
in support of the Beijing students who led the China protests.
   The statue was built by artists and by students from the Academy
for Performing Arts, the Chinese University of Hong Kong and the
Hong Kong Polytechnic.
   The statue faces north to China. Wah said he would ask the
government to allow a permanent place for it.
   The original statue was knocked down by a tank in Tiananmen
Square on June 4 after troops rolled in to crush the 7-week-old
movement for greater social freedoms.
   China's state-controlled media said last week that nearly 100
soldiers and police died and that thousands were injured, while
about 100 civilians died and nearly 1,000 were injured. Chinese
witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may
have been as high as 3,000.
</TEXT>
