<FIRST>r i AM-Syria-Palestinians     06-18 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Syria-Palestinians,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syria Frees 145 Arafat Fighters In Apparent Goodwill Gesture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria has freed 185 Palestinian guerrillas
and allied Sunni Moslem fighters from prisons in an apparent move
toward reconciliation with PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, Arab sources
said Sunday.
   The guerrillas _ 145 members of Arafat's Fatah movement and 40
members of the Sunni Moslem Tawhid faction _ were taken to the
Syrian-controlled north Lebanon city of Tripoli on Tuesday, the
sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Neither Syrian officials nor the Palestine Liberation
Organization had any comment on the report.
   The move was seen as part of behind-the-scenes moves by Syrian
President Hafez Assad and Arafat to bridge a 6-year-old rift that
has long been a key obstacle to Arab unity.
   The Syrian action could signal a new era in relations with the
PLO. Although earlier reconciliation efforts have collapsed, the
release indicated a stronger Syrian commitment to improving
relations than in the past.
   Damascus has been increasingly isolated politically since the end
of the Iran-Iraq war, in which it backed Persian Iran against Arab
Iraq. The war ended with a U.N.-mediated cease-fire Aug. 20.
   Syria has also been bogged down fighting the Christians in
Lebanon. Damascus entered that country's civil war under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate but later sided with the Moslem Druse militias.
   The Syrians have held some 2,000 Palestinians and members of the
Sunni fundamentalist Tawhid since 1983. Tawhid is based in Tripoli
and has long been allied with Arafat.
   The Palestinians were mainly rounded up in Syria after Assad
split with Arafat and expelled him from his headquarters in Damascus.
   The Syrians had alleged that Arafat's efforts to negotiate with
Israel betrayed the Arab cause. Arafat said the Syrians tried to
assassinate him.
   Among the Palestinians held was Arafat's representative in
Damascus, Mohammad Amali. It was not known whether he was among
those freed.
   It was not known where the released Palestinians went from
Tripoli. But it was likely they would move on to Tunis, the PLO
headquarters, or possibly to PLO guerrilla bases in North Yemen.
   Syria has been under increasing pressure from the Soviet Union
and moderate Arabs to reconcile with Arafat.
   They made an effort to patch up their differences last year after
Arafat's military commander, Khalil al-Wazir, better known as Abu
Jihad, was assassinated.
   But that attempt foundered because of the deep-rooted hostility
between the two sides.
   The worldwide support Arafat has gained from the 18-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, and his diplomatic successes since launching his peace
initiative with Israel, widened the gulf.
   Assad has long sought to depose Arafat and wrest control of the
Palestinian cause to bolster his prestige in the Arab world and his
bargaining power in any negotiations with Israel.
   Assad and Arafat met on the sidelines of the Arab summit in
Casablanca, Morocco, in May. Both sides sought to play down the
sessions following the failure of last year's rapprochement attempt.
   However, informed Palestinian sources said Arafat insisted Assad
free the Palestinians as a sign of Syria's good will.
</TEXT>
