<FIRST>r i AM-Romania-Hungary     06-18 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Hungary,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Protests Comments at Nagy Reburial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania summoned Hungary's ambassador to
protest what it said were fascist and anti-Romanian comments made
during the reburial of Hungarian leader Imre Nagy, who led the 1956
revolution against Soviet rule.
   The government issued its protest Saturday to Hungarian
Ambassador Pal Szuts in Bucharest, the Romanian capital, the
Romanian state-run Agerpres news agency said Sunday.
   The protest is certain to increase friction between the two
Warsaw Pact nations. Relations already have been seriously strained
by alleged discrimination against Romania's ethnic Hungarians.
   Nagy's reburial in Budapest on Friday ``turned into a
manifestation clearly fascist, anti-socialist in nature, aimed
against the Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party, against ...
communism and the Warsaw Treaty,'' said the report.
   The government of President Nicolae Ceausescu was apparently
galled by the participation at the funeral ceremony of several
Romanian refugees.
   Nagy and four of his closest associates were solemnly reburied at
Budapest's Rakoskeresztur cemetery in the same plot where their
bodies had been dumped following their executions in 1958.
   The reburial was hugely symbolic for Hungary, which has embarked
on a series of democratic reforms and has rehabilitated Nagy's image
in the process. The revolt he led was crushed by Soviet troops.
   While Hungary has become increasingly liberal, Romanian remains
among the most hardline of the East bloc nations.
   Thousands of Romanians and ethnic Hungarian citizens of Romania
have fled the country to escape alleged political persecution and
worsening economic hardships.
   Agerpres said heads of diplomatic missions of ``certain
countries'' were ``received'' at the foreign ministry in Bucharest
and informed of the Romanian protest,
   Romanian citizens, including ethnic Hungarians, voiced ``their
profound indignation at the revisionist ... and anti-communist
manifestation held ... (during the) reburial of some Hungarian
citizens,'' the official report said.
   Agerpres said Romanian newspapers, radio and television stations
had received ``many letters and phone calls'' from angered citizens.
   There was no immediate comment from Hungary and the Hungarian
ambassador's response during the meeting was not known.
</TEXT>
