<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-CentralAmerica     06-18 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Central America,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Turns up Rhetoric on Second Foray to Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With no particular new policy to push, Vice
President Dan Quayle used his recent trip Central America to
dispense hardline rhetoric and display a more experienced U.S.
leader than the novice who met the Latin presidents four months ago.
   Quayle was well briefed for his three-day tour of Guatemala,
Honduras, Costa Rica and El Salvador where his mission was to
underline existing U.S. policies. He focused on finding ways to
criticize Panama's ruling Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government while singing the praises
of the democratic governments in the four countries he visited.
   He also made points with a consultative approach that went over
well in a region accustomed to a more dogmatic tradition from their
northern neighbor.
   ``It's not just the Reagan administration Rambo _ gung-ho guy
going around the world just firing machine guns. It's someone that
is willing to engage in dialogue and wants to know what the rest of
the world thinks,'' said Francisco Aguilar Urbina, adviser to Costa
Rica's President Oscar Arias.
   Quayle was attentive and ``inquiring,'' he said, adding, ``It's a
different Dan Quayle,'' than the brand new vice president who met
the Latin heads of state for the first time at the Venezuelan
inauguration in early February.
   ``He may not be the foreign affairs expert that anyone would
expect to come, but he sure gives a good impression,'' said Urbina.
   Still, Quayle publicly upbraided El Salvadoran rightist
politician Roberto D'Abuisson, who is accused in many quarters of
ties to death squad activity.
   Some who agreed with Quayle's message that D'Abuisson should not
embarrass his party's new president felt, nonetheless, that the
blunt admonition lacked the sophisticated tone that Latins find more
appropriate, said Costa Rican presidential adviser Guido Fernandez.
   Fernandez, former ambassador to the United States, participated
in the Quayle visit during his last days as information minister
before leaving government for a business venture.
   Stating that Latin audiences found Quayle's shouting for the
ouster of Noriega a bit imperialistic-sounding, Fernandez concluded
Quayle remains in ``a learning process.''
   Subtlety, however, apparently was not Quayle's intention.
   He ventured into new rhetorical territory that edged him beyond
public pronouncements of other top U.S. officials and roused some
Capitol Hill concerns that he was trying to make inroads for those
who would pull President Bush more to the right on Central America.
   Seizing on reports that Nicaragua was geared up to supply arms to
Panama against a possible U.S. military attack, Quayle raised the
specter of a Cuba-Nicaragua-Panamana ``axis'' threatening the
hemisphere's democracies.
   Quayle also vowed, without elaborating, that the United States
will always have a ``moral obligation'' to the Contra rebels of
Nicaragua.
   The Salvadoran military's recent discovery of a huge cache of
Soviet bloc arms gave Quayle fodder to accuse the Sandinistas of
arming the Salvadoran guerillas.
   Arias, in a news conference with Quayle, limited his criticism of
the Sandinistas to accusing them of enacting unfair election laws.
But Arias also separated himself from Quayle's stridency,
emphasizing the need to include rather than isolate Nicaragua in
efforts to reach peace.
   William Walker, U.S. ambassador to El Salvador, defended Quayle's
direct style in talks not only with D'Abuisson, but with leftist
political leaders Guillermo Ungo and Ruben Zamora. Quayle told them
to urge the guerrillas to lay down their arms.
   ``The vice president handled it beautifully. He said just the
right things. He certainly wasn't inexperienced,'' Walker said. He
called the trip successful, saying, ``It wasn't a spectacular
breakthrough. It wasn't supposed to be that.''
   The trip's initial purpose was a show of support for President
Alfredo Cristiani's new government in El Salvador, with friendship
stops in the three other U.S.-backed Central American democracies.
   But just before Quayle left last week, President Bush told him to
step up the focus on Panama, an administration official said.
   There is some administration concern that the Organization of
American States might go too soft on Noriega in its effort to
mediate a transfer of power from him to an elected government, said
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Quayle emphasized _ especially with the Guatemalan foreign
minister who is a member of the OAS mediating team _ that the United
States wants Noriega to leave his country and would look unfavorably
on any resolution allowing him to stay even if he relinquished power.
   The trip also solidified Quayle's personal relationships with the
Latin leaders, who observed a more knowledgeable Quayle than the one
they met at the inauguration of Venezuela's new president Carlos
Andres Perez.
   ``I noticed the difference,'' said Fernandez. ``In Caracas, he
seemed to be astonished, meeting new people. Now he seems more
relaxed. He pays a lot of attention. He concentrates very much.''
</TEXT>
