<FIRST>r i AM-PuertoRico-Quake     06-18 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Quake,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Puerto Rico Shaken by Moderate Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook Puerto
Rico on Sunday, but no injuries or damage were reported by the Civil
Defense.
   Seismologist William McCann, of the the U.S. Geological Survey
Office at the University of Puerto Rico, said the quake occured just
after 10 a.m.
   McCann said instruments recorded a 4.8 magnitude on the Richter
scale. The epicenter was 120 miles southwest of San Juan in the Mona
Passage, which divides Puerto Rico and Hispaniola island.
   Puerto Rico Civil Defense Director Heriberto Acevedo said the
agency had no reports of injury or damages.
   Mona Passage is a high seismic zone registering some 2,000 small
tremors a year.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6
severe damage.
</TEXT>
