<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Catholics-Hispanics     06-18 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catholics-Hispanics,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Catholic Bishops Accuses Protestant Groups Of `Deceptive'
Recruiting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops charged that some of the nation's
largest Protestant denominations have a plan for proselytizing
Hispanic Catholics into their churches ``in a very deceptive way.''
   The charge was made by Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis, who
commented in a news conference Saturday evening and then elaborated
on them later in an interview during the bishops' annual spring
meeting at Seton Hall University.
   May mentioned the Southern Baptist Convention.
   ``I think that's an unfair statement,'' the Rev. Daniel Vestal,
pastor at Dunwoody Baptist Church in Atlanta and the unsuccessful
candidate last week for the presidency of the 14.5 million-member
Southern Baptist Conference, said Sunday.
   ``I can't speak for all Protestant groups but I know the Southern
Baptists offer a message of hope and redemption. That attracts
people regardless of race,'' Vestal said.
   Jay Strack, president of the Conference of Southern Baptist
Evangelists; Stan Hastey, executive director of the Southern Baptist
Alliance, a moderate group within the demonination, did not
immediate return telephone calls left with their offices Sunday
morning seeking comment.
   At their annual spring meeting, held at Seton Hall University
this weekend, the bishops voted to emphasize evangelization in their
celebration of the fifth centenary of European explorers'
introduction of Roman Catholic faith in the Americas in 1992 and to
start work on a document to give black Catholics a greater role in
the church.
   Minority membership of the Catholic Church is growing. A wave of
immigrants from Spanish-speaking nations and a relatively high birth
rate have made Hispanics the fastest-growing group of U.S.
Catholics, making up an estimated third of the 53 million-member
denomination. In part because of immigration from the West Indies
and Haiti, the number of black Catholics has risen from 900,000 to 2
million in the past 20 years.
   However, church officials say conservative Protestant groups are
increasingly wooing minority Catholics.
   May said fundamentalist churches have ``a very clearly fashioned
plan to entice people away from the church in a very deceptive way.''
   He said some fundamentalist churches go so far as to feature
Catholic art and music in their churches to draw Hispanics in, and
then start teaching anti-Catholic doctrines to keep the new converts
from returning to Catholicism.
   In a report to the bishops, the Rev. Allan Figueroa Deck, a
theologian and specialist in Hispanic studies, said one national
study has found at least 60,000 Hispanics leave the church each
year, and a million have left in the past 15 years.
   Catholic officials also admit the church has driven some minority
members away through apathy and insensitivity.
   Deck said that while Hispanic Catholics struggle to be noticed in
the Catholic Church, evangelical sects are providing numerous
Spanish-speaking ministers and small churches ``especially
appropriate for immigrants who need all the personal communal
support they can get.''
   ``We've been developing leadership among these racial groups,''
said Vestal of the Baptists. ``It's a fact that churches grow when
they are led by people from their own culture.''
   ``The Southern Baptists are very effective in promoting
leadership within ethnic or racial groups,'' Vestal said.
   In a pastoral statement by the Bishops' Committee on Black
Catholics, the nation's 13 black prelates said there is a serious
attrition of black Catholics from the church.
   Sister Thea Bowman of Canton, Miss., a black nun, said in an
emotional appeal to the bishops that black Catholics sometimes feel
``like a motherless child'' in the church.
   The pastoral statement proposed by the black bishops, drawn up in
response to a National Black Catholic Pastoral Plan devised by 1,500
black Catholics at a 1987 congress in Washington, calls for giving
blacks more positions of responsibility and integrating
African-American cultural symbols into liturgies and churches.
   After two days of business meetings, the bishops spent Sunday
largely in religious observances, gathering for morning and evening
prayers and concelebrating Mass at Sacred Heart Cathedral in Newark.
The bishops were scheduled to meet in excutive session Monday to
conclude the four-day meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
