<DOCNO> AP890618-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ThompsonExecution     06-18 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thompson Execution,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condemned Man Rejects Appeals Before Early Morning Execution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Execution scheduled at 5 a.m. EDT Monday; may stand for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A death row inmate facing a predawn
execution for a Reno murder continued to reject available appeals
Sunday amid controversy over his 11th-hour admission to other
killings.
   William Paul Thompson, 52, said he could see guards preparing the
death chamber only 10 feet away from his cell.
   ``I'm looking at the car they're fixing to take me home in,'' he
said of the death chamber. ``They're gassing it up now.''
   Thompson told The Associated Press on Saturday, in the only
interview he granted, that he killed six people, including the
contract murder of a federal prosecutor in Oklahoma in 1983.
   In Tulsa, Okla., U.S. Attorney Tony Graham said he wasn't aware
of any prosecutor in the state who had disappeared or was killed in
1983. Graham said Thompson's statement sounds ``somewhat
preposterous'' and he didn't intend to investigate the claim.
   Said Bill Price, who recently stepped down as U.S. attorney in
Oklahoma City, said, ``If a federal prosecutor had been killed in
Oklahoma, I would definitely know about it. That (claim) is
categorically false.''
   Thompson declined further interviews, prison officials said.
   No reviews by the Nevada Pardons Board or state Supreme Court
were planned following Thompson's statement Wednesday in Washoe
County District Court insisting that he die for killing a man in
Reno.
   And no 11th-hour petitions were likely from the federal public
defender or the American Civil Liberties Union, although assistant
federal defender Pat Flanagan said a petition was prepared if
Thompson decided he wanted to try for a stay.
   Thompson said he didn't want to stop his execution by lethal
injection because he's ready to die and might kill again if he
remains alive.
   ``They're letting a guilty man die with dignity,'' he said. ``I
never thought I'd be thanking someone for letting me die, never in a
million years.''
   He said he has found religion in the past several months and now
is ``paying back to society the only thing I have to offer it.''
   ``When you give everything you got, that should be enough. My
death is payment to everyone I've ever hurt, my family, the victims'
families.''
   Thompson was sentenced to die for the 1984 killing of a transient
in Reno. After that sentence, he was convicted of killing two
brothers who were camping near Auburn, Calif.
   Thompson said the Reno victim, ``just got in my way'' while he
was on the run from the killings of the brothers who, he said, he
shot because they were drug informants.
   He recounted a life of crime and alcoholism that started at age
12 in Texas, and said he'd spent more than half his life behind bars
for various crimes.
   He said that in 1983 he carried out three contract murders,
including the claimed slaying of a prosecutor in Oklahoma, ``for
things they'd done against my friends. I went looking for these
people.''
   The other murders were in New York and in Kansas, he said. He
wouldn't reveal the names of the victims or the people who hired him.
   Thompson said he wasn't a ``Mafia hit man,'' but ``I was
convenient, and in the trade, and they just asked me if I would do a
job for them.''
   The last person executed in the United States was Michael
Lindsay, executed May 26 in Alabama's electric chair, the 111th
person executed since the U.S. Supreme Court revived the death
penalty in 1976.
   Carroll Edward Cole was the last person executed by lethal
injection in Nevada, in December 1985, after confessing to killing
more than a dozen women as revenge for an abusive mother. That
followed the 1979 Nevada gas chamber execution of convicted killer
Jesse Bishop.
</TEXT>
