<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessWinner     06-18 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Winner,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventh-grader Draws On Personal Experience For Prize-Winning Essay</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen-year-old Lashanda Daniels didn't have to
spend any time in the library doing research for her prize-winning
essay on the homeless. For five months she slept at a city shelter,
sharing one room with her mother and four brothers.
   During the months she spent there, Miss Daniels told only her
closest friends where she went each night. Her family has since
managed to find an apartment, but the memories of the shelter remain
vivid.
   ``First you hate yourself for being in that predicament,'' she
wrote in a composition that placed second in a citywide contest.
``Then that feeling of hate spreads towards those around you. You
find yourself being jealous of those who have a home and you feel as
if everyone looks down on you.''
   Living in a shelter was infinitely preferable to scrounging on
the streets, but it was a depressing and embarrassing experience,
said the Timilty Middle School seventh-grader.
   Miss Daniels spent some of her free time reading books at the
shelter, but she said her grades slipped during her stay.
   In her essay, written shortly after she left the shelter, she
described self-pity as the enemy of the homeless.
   ``You feel like you want to just let everything go and sometimes
that happens. If you are not a very strong-willed person, it will
happen,'' she wrote. ``You have to stick to your guns, and grin and
bear it sometimes to make your life's goal a reality.''
   The contest, ``What Can We Do About Homelessness?'' was sponsored
by the police department and a radio station and drew more than 600
entries. Other winners suggested remedies, such as more government
aid, but none wrote from the personal perspective of Miss Daniels,
said her English teacher, Daisy Droge.
   The essay was all Miss Daniels' work. A teacher typed up the
draft copy and made only minor editing changes, said Mrs. Droge.
   Miss Daniels' suggestions for the homeless include city-run
workshops on getting a job, more low-income housing and more
shelters. But the main thrust of her essay was a call for
understanding and self-help.
   ``I don't care what your situation is or what it may become,''
she wrote. ``Whether it is homeless or helpless, there is a way that
you as an individual can make things happen for yourself.''
   Before moving to Boston last year, the Daniels family shared a
one-room apartment with a grandmother in Detroit, Miss Daniels said.
She says the family decided to move to Boston because they have
several relatives in the area and because her mother thought the
city would be safer for her daughter and four boys, ranging from 11
to 17 years old.
   All of the children are in school and her mother is taking
college courses, trying to get training so she can get a good job,
Miss Daniels said. She said she hears only infrequently from her
father, who left the family some time ago.
   By the time she wrote the essay, her family had been out of the
Boston City Shelter for about a month and she said she no longer
felt embarrassed about her stay there.
   ``My mother was embarrassed. She didn't think I could write
anything that good,'' the teen-ager said. ``I said, `Well, now's
your chance to see what I can really do.'''
   In May, she learned she had placed second in the middle school
division of the contest. Half of her $250 prize went to her mother
and $70 went for summer camp. The rest was split between a bank
account and a lavish lunch with her mother and teacher.
   Miss Daniels, says she's determined to go to college and study
for a career, but she can't totally shake her memories of the
shelter.
   ``Every time my mother gets a check, I make sure she pays the
rent so we won't get put out,'' she said.
   ``It's not easy,'' she said. ``It's a good thing that you have
somewhere to go, that you have a roof over your head, but it's not
an easy life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
