<FIRST>r w AM-Jackson-DCStatehood     06-18 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-DC Statehood,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Endorses Statehood for District of Columbia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE RUMSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson endorsed statehood for the
District of Columbia on Sunday, saying the city deserves
``emancipation and empowerment.''
   Speaking at a packed northwest Washington church, Jackson said
the district should have full representation in Congress. He did not
mention his own reported interest in running for mayor of the city.
   Saying Washington should be ``a city on the hill,'' Jackson
ticked off problems facing the district, including drugs, high
crime, poverty and hunger.
   In a speech spiced with biblical references, Jackson likened the
push for statehood to Moses' struggle to free the Israelites and
black Americans' emancipation from slavery.
   ``We should be praying, God give us statehood, God give us
self-determination,'' Jackson said.
   The District of Columbia has a city government but its delegate
to Congress, Democrat Walter Fauntroy, is non-voting. The district's
mayor, Democrat Marion Barry, has been plagued by questions about
alleged drug use and his association with a man convicted of drug
charges in the Virgin Islands. Barry has repeatedly denied ever
using drugs.
   There are more residents in the nation's capital than in several
states, including Vermont, Delaware and Wyoming, Jackson said. The
district's population is about 360,000.
   ``In every western democracy people in the capital city have
voting representation in the national legislature,'' Jackson said
after the speech. He said he has scheduled meetings on Capitol Hill
this week to discuss the issue.
   Jackson said early this month he will move to Washington this
year but that he had made no decision on whether to make the city
his legal voting residence. He has said he will not run for mayor
against Barry, but has not indicated what he would do if Barry did
not seek re-election.
</TEXT>
