<FIRST>r i AM-Libya-China     06-18 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-China,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Says Chinese Government Prompted Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi said the Chinese
government prompted the recent pro-democracy demonstrations through
its political and economic policies, the official Libyan news agency
JANA reported Sunday.
   He also criticized the students who led the demonstrations that
were crushed by army assaults June 3-4.
   JANA quoted Gadhafi as saying the students should have created a
Libyan-style political system instead of ``setting up disorganized
pickets and chaos.''
   Gadhafi, in an interview with Japanese television, said, ``It is
socialism which saved China from ruin and death,'' according to the
JANA report monitored in Rome.
   China's ``opening to the West led to tendencies of imitating the
wealthy Western society and ... the opening to imperialism and
consumer markets led the people to run toward vile and unnecessary
consumer goods,'' he said.
   JANA reported Gadhafi said if China had established a Libyan-type
socialist system, with ``people's congresses,'' ``the people would
not have resorted to violence to express their demands.''
   Gadhafi did not mention the hundreds of people killed in the army
crackdown.
   Gadhafi also used the interview to make overtures to the Bush
administration.
   ``I believe that the new American administration is wise and has
learned from past lessons,'' he said, according to JANA. ``I believe
(President) Bush is a non-hostile political personality.''
   He also said he hoped Libya would have balanced relations with
both the Soviet Union and United States.
   Libya and the United States had relations strained to the point
of hostilities during the administration of former President Ronald
Reagan. U.S. warplanes bombed Libya in May 1986 after Reagan claimed
that Gadhafi sponsored international terrorism.
</TEXT>
