<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS brites rdp to DELETE Rockville, Md.-item about boy and
income tax refund, which substantially repeats item that moved Wednesday,
June 14. Item is replaced with unrelated story to make a rdp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT PROSPECT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An expensive showdog who understood
only French commands was found Sunday, nearly a week after he got
out of a cage at O'Hare International Airport and said au revoir to
baggage handlers.
   The 3-year-old Belgian Malinois named Korsair, valued as high as
$50,000, was found taking a breather on a back-yard deck a few miles
from the airport. Police, called to the scene by a homeowner who
thought the pup was just any old stray, used dog biscuits to win
over the pup long enough to get him on a leash.
   ``He was a little thin and has a small foot injury,'' but
otherwise appeared in good shape, said police Sgt. Roland Lischalk.
   The dog slipped from his cage on June 12 while his owner,
Frenchman Daniel Paul, changed planes at O'Hare while traveling from
San Francisco to Lansing, Mich.
   Korsair responds only to French commands and paid not the
slightest mind to airline employees who chased after him, hollering
in English.
   Where the dog has been for the past week, no one knows, but he
would have had no trouble dealing with the fences surrounding the
7,000-acre airport.
   ``He's trained to jump fences,'' said United Airlines spokeswoman
Sara Dornacker. ``He can jump 8 feet.''
   The dog was turned over to its handler, Gerald A. Rousseau.
   Korsair's owner values the dog at $20,000 because of his
pedigree, stud value and championship record. Louis Auslander,
chairman of the American Kennel Club, said the dog may be worth as
much as $50,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's in a name?
   Is the proper designation for the metropolitian area of 1.4
million people at the confluence of the James River and the
Chesapeake Bay the Tidewater? River Cities? Greater Norfolk? Hampton
Roads?
   Some wags have suggested the area's seven largest cities _
Norfolk, Virginia Beach, Portsmouth, Suffolk, Chesapeake, Newport
News and Hampton _ simply be dubbed the Septuplex Cities by the Sea.
The eight smaller cities could then be known as the Octaburbs.
   ``I think `Hampton Roads' has a nice ring to it,'' offered Arthur
L. Collins, executive director of the Southeast Virginia Planning
District Commission.
   The folks at Hampton Roads Chamber of Commerce, of course, agree,
if only because they would have to change their stationery if they
didn't. The chamber is pushing the designation for the 17 localities
clustered around the harbor, which laid claim to the Hampton Roads
name at least two centuries ago.
   The chamber chides those who insist on continuing calling the
area ``Tidewater,'' an appellation popular in the 1960s and 1970s.
The U.S. Postal Service even picked up on the moniker using
``Tidewater'' as the area's postmark starting in 1975.
   After it was lobbied by the city councils and business groups,
the Postal Service began postmarking letters in 1983 as ``Hampton
Roads, Va.''
   But there are still some holdouts against the anti-Tidewater
tide, both private and public.
   There is Tidewater Tides baseball team and the Tidewater Regional
Transit Board, for example. The telephone book lists 459 businesses
who begin their company name with Tidewater. Only 125 use the
officially approved Hampton Roads.
   ``We wouldn't change our name for anything,'' said Steve
Rubenstein, general manager of Tidewater Gook, a Virginia Beach
company that distributes gunk solvents along the East Coast.
   ``What's in a name?'' asked Barbara Henley, head of the regional
transit board and a Virginia Beach councilwoman. ``I don't think
people identify with Hampton Roads any better than they identify
with Tidewater.''
   Changing the AAA farm team to the Hampton Road Tides is not an
option, according to the team's general manager. ``I would fight to
the death because I think it's ridiculous,'' said Dave Rosenfield,
who said he likes the aliteration of the team's current name.
</TEXT>
