<HEAD>Thunderstorms Gather Near the Tennessee Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered, mostly light rain fell across much of the nation's
eastern half Sunday.
   Showers and occasional thunderstorms were scattered over eastern
Texas, Florida, Georgia, South Carolina, Missouri, southern
Illinois, western Kentucky and western Tennessee, and from
northeastern New York to northern New England.
   Small hail fell near Canaan, Vt., and a thunderstorm produced
winds gusting to 46 mph in Augusta, Maine.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, all rainfall was less than
0.25 of an inch, the National Weather Service reported.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Port Angeles, Wash., and San Simeon, Calif., to 111 in
Yuma, Ariz. Sunday's low for the Lower 48 states was 35 degrees in
Butte, Mont.
   The forecast for Monday called for showers and thunderstorms from
central New York to southern lower Michigan, eastern Indiana, Ohio,
western Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Kentucky, Tennessee, Alabama,
Georgia and much of Florida; and showers in the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 60s from northern Oregon
through Washington state, and along the northern and southern coast
of California; in the 90s in much of Florida, Louisiana, much of
Texas, western Oklahoma, Kansas, western Missouri, Nebraska, the
southwestern half of South Dakota, from southern Montana to much of
Nevada, Utah, northern New Mexico, and northern Arizona; in the 90s
to near 105 degrees in southwestern Texas; in the 90s to near 115
through much of inland California and the desert Southwest; and
generally in the 70s and 80s over the rest of the nation.
