<FIRST>r a AM-UAWConvention     06-18 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Convention,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bieber Lashes Out at UAW Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers union President Owen
Bieber lashed out at union dissidents Sunday, saying their dispute
with his administration insults the intelligence of union members.
   Bieber, speaking at the opening of the week-long UAW
Constitutional Convention, wasted little time in his hour-long
speech in taking on the New Directions movement, the biggest
internal challenge a union administration has faced in 40 years.
   ``To be frank, I think those who say that workers don't want
change in the workplace _ who insist that the old ways were always
the best ways _ are insulting the intelligence of UAW members,''
Bieber said amid cheers from about 2,000 convention delegates.
   The New Directions movement, led by Jerry Tucker of UAW Region 5
in St. Louis, has criticized the union's administration for being
too chummy with automakers through joint worker-management programs
on the shop floor. Bieber and his followers have responded that the
New Directions backers aren't facing the reality of a changing
workplace.
   ``It is precisely because we weren't afraid to move forward and
raise new issues and new demands with employers that we have stayed
ahead of the pack on ... a whole range of areas where we have
reconized a need and worked to find solutions for our members and
their families,'' he said.
   Labor observers have said Bieber doesn't exert the strong
leadership style of his two immediate predecessors _ Douglas Fraser
and Leonard Woodcock _ and that a stronger showing at this
convention would help defuse New Directions.
   Bieber, defending the UAW leadership against New Directions
charges that it has gone soft, said the 1-million-member union
authorized strikes 817 times in the past three years, and more than
2,700 members now are on strike.
   ``So let me assure you, and let me warn any employers who may
have formed the wrong idea of where this union is heading,'' Bieber
said. ``Where our power of persuasion fails, we will use the
persuasion of power without hesitation.''
   He also said the recent cooperative agreements might not fit into
the union's future.
   ``If the joint programs get off the track or if joint programs
are abused, we're going to fix them or we're going to throw them
out,'' he said.
   In his speech, Bieber also called for UAW members to gear up for
the nation's 1990 mid-term elections, a tougher foreign trade
policy, and for corporations to pay more attention to their U.S.
workers, a theme of a current UAW television and print campaign.
   The convention concludes Friday after reports from several
committees and elections of officers, in which Bieber faces no
opposition.
</TEXT>
