<FIRST>r a AM-ExchangeStudentSlain     06-18 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exchange Student Slain,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Student Slain; Gunman At Large</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old Japanese exchange student
was shot to death by a man who may have eluded police afterward by
briefly holding a couple hostage in their apartment, police said
Sunday.
   Police suggested no motive for the slaying and said the gunman
was still at large.
   Ai Toyoshima, who arrived in this country just two months ago,
died Saturday morning from a single gunshot to the chest.
   ``She was very beautiful, very nice,'' said Hideo Yanagi, 15, a
friend and classmate. ``It's terrible what happened. It's very sad.
I cannot believe that could happen in America.''
   A passerby found Toyoshima wounded and dying Friday night in a
field not far from where police believe she got off a local bus. She
had boarded the bus with a friend at the American Language Programs
school in nearby Campbell where both were students.
   Police believe the gunman got off the bus at the same stop as
Toyoshima.
   ``He took her off the sidewalk into a dark park with a gun,''
said Police Lt. Jim Terry on Sunday. Terry declined to speculate on
the gunman's possible motive or divulge further details of the
attack.
   Toyoshima described her assailant to a police officer who speaks
Japanese before she died in a hospital Saturday morning, police said.
   Shortly before the student's body was found Friday night, a man
police believe was the gunman tried to steal a car outside a liquor
store.
   Cruising police officers noticed the car's owner wrestling with
the would-be thief and chased him into an apartment complex. A
couple in the complex were briefly held hostage by a man who is
still at large and who police believe was the gunman.
   ``He told us to be quiet, he told us not to move, so we didn't,''
said Jean Ann Gritter, 57, after the man had left through a window
of the Gritters' family room.
   Police had blocked off the streets and just a few houses away
were searching with flashlights and dogs.
   ``It's pretty obvious this is the same guy,'' said Police Lt.
Richard Couser. ``We are still pursuing him, but he is still very
much on the loose. We don't think he is still in the neighborhood.''
   Japanese exchange student Junko Owaki was killed in Fremont, east
of San Francisco, in February 1986 and robbed of $2,200. Two
teen-agers are serving sentences in that slaying.
</TEXT>
