<FIRST>u i AM-Angola     06-18 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>African Leaders to Set Terms for Angolan Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African leaders meeting in Zaire next
week will seek an end to Angola's 14-year civil war by setting terms
for talks between the Marxist government and U.S.-backed rebels,
diplomatic sources and media reports said Sunday.
   The meeting of nearly a quarter of the continent's leaders will
set a cease-fire timetable and establish contact groups between
Angola's Marxist government and the right-wing National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA, the sources said.
   In a related development, a rebel spokesman said UNITA leader
Jonas Savimbi has agreed not to participate in a 10-man peace
commission and he denied reports Savimbi has accepted exile.
   Ivory Coast President Felix Houphouet-Boigny will mediate during
the Zaire meeting, said the sources, who did not give exact dates
for the gathering. They said the meeting will place either in the
capital of Kinshasa or northeastern Gbadolite.
   Angola's official ANGOP news agency said the summit will
``legitimize internationally,'' government attempts to end the
devastating war.
   South African news reports Sunday said Zairean President Mobutu
Sese Seko, a staunch ally of Savimbi, is principle architect of the
talks.
   Alcides Sakala, a rebel spokesman in Lisbon, was quoted by Tempo
magazine as saying preliminary talks could bring a transitional
Angolan government as early as July, and that Savimbi has ``agreed
to withdraw to New York for some time.''
   In Washington, rebel spokesman Manuel Mundombe said Sakala was
misquoted.
   ``It was just a rumor that Savimbi would accept exile,'' he said
Saturday.
   Spokeswomen at the State Department and the White House said they
knew nothing about Savimbi coming to the United States.
   Despite offering clemency for rebels, Angola's government
repeatedly has refused to treat with Savimbi.
   Diplomats in Lisbon suggest the charismatic rebel leader could
accept a two-year exile in Morocco, the Ivory Coast or the United
States, before returning to stand for presidential elections after a
period of transitional government.
   Previous attempts have been blocked by Savimbi's refusal to sit
out the peace process despite growing pressure from South Africa,
which helped arm the rebels, and black African nations.
   The rebels have been fighting to share power since Angola gained
independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The scheduled meeting in Zaire follows a U.S.-brokered accord
under which South Africa agreed to give Namibia independence and
halt aid to Angolan rebels in exchange for the withdrawal of 50,000
Cuban troops helping the Luanda government fight Savimbi's
guerrillas.
   In March, the rebels declared a unilateral four-month cease-fire
which Sakala said will be extended through July 24.
</TEXT>
