<FIRST>r a AM-SeattleQuake 2ndLd-Writethru a0712 06-18 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seattle Quake, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0712,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Light Earthquake Reported in Seattle Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with no damage reported, comments from geophysicist.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A light earthquake shook the Seattle area Sunday
afternoon, but no damage was reported, authorities said.
   The 1:38 p.m. quake shook the Puget Sound area and was also felt
in Tacoma and Olympia, and as far north as Victoria and Sidney on
Vancouver Island in Canada, the U.S. Geological Survey said.
   The temblor, which measured 4.4 on the Richter scale and was 30
miles deep, was centered about 10 miles southwest of Bremerton,
which is 25 miles west of Seattle, said Steve Malone of the
University of Washington Geophysics Center.
   ``I'd be surprised if any damage occurred from an earthquake that
deep,'' Malone said. There were no reports of damage.
   An earthquake measured at 4.3 on the Richter scale occurred in
the same general area on March 11, 1988, said Don Finley, of the
USGS office in Golden, Colo.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   An earthquake of 3.5 can cause slight damage in the local area, 4
moderate damage, 5 considerable damage and 6 severe damage. A 7
reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy
damage.
</TEXT>
