<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     06-18 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiled Guerrilla Leaders Come Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of guerrilla officials flew back
to their homeland Sunday, many after nearly 30 years in exile, with
promises to fight hard but fair during independence elections.
   Hage Geingob, elections director of the South-West African
Peoples' Organization, who fought 23 years against South African
occupation of Africa's last colony, kissed the tarmac when he
stepped off a Zambia Airways plane.
   Most of the 150 SWAPO dignitaries sang as they walked to the
terminal building at sunset. They included 11 members of the
organization's executive committee and Politburo.
   About 8,000 people had gathered to greet them, but only 200 were
left to welcome them because the plane was delayed three hours by
technical difficulties.
   The homecoming was marred by isolated incidents. A bus carrying
guerrilla supporters reportedly was shot at and a stone was thrown
through the window. One person was arrested carrying a firearm in
the demonstration. But the only casualty was a man who apparently
waved a sign of an opposition party. He was stabbed.
   Most exiles came from Lusaka, Zambia, on the same plane that last
week brought the first of some 41,000 refugees due to return to
Namibia under a U.N. independence plan.
   Sam Nujoma, president of the guerrilla organization, was not
among returnees. Officials say they have to make sure it is safe for
him to return.
   In an emotional speech, Geingob told reporters he knew he was
home when he saw police at the airport. Paramilitary police played a
major role in the war and members have been integrated into the
regular police force. Geingob said free and fair elections are
impossible until the counter-insurgency policemen are discharged.
   He said the return of the guerrilla leaders, expected to win a
majority in November elections, symbolizes ``a new dawn of
reconciliation and peace.''
   ``We promise a clean fight but a hell of a fight,'' he said. ``It
is therefore our sincere hope that the era of the bullet has truly
given way to the era of the ballot box.''
   Geingob declined to comment on the 200 prisoners held by his
organization as spies or dissidents. He would not say why they
denied the International Committee of the Red Cross access to the
prisoners held at camps in other African countries.
   ``That is no longer our problem. We have released them,'' he said.
   Geingob praised those who died in the war.
   ``It pains one to think how happy they would have been to see us
arrive here today. But I know they would not want us to mourn them
on an occasion like this, but to pledge that we shall see through to
the end what they died for.''
   South Africa agreed to give independence to this mineral-rich
former German colony in exchange for the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban
troops helping Angola's government fight U.S.-armed rebels.
</TEXT>
