<FIRST>r a AM-Father'sDayBriefs     06-18 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Father's Day Briefs,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dad's Day Doings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dad may feel pretty special on Father's Day,
but he apparently got less recognition than mom did on her day a
month earlier, say representatives of greeting card and telephone
companies.
   An estimated 90 million Father's Day cards were mailed this year,
compared with 145 million cards mailed for Mother's Day, said
Barbara Miller of Hallmark Cards Inc. in Kansas City, Mo.
   Hallmark makes 1,200 different Mother's Day cards, compared with
900 Father's Day cards, she said.
   Father's Day ranks as the third busiest holiday in the telephone
business after Christmas _ and Mother's Day.
   AT&amp;T estimated there would be 42 million long-distance calls on
Sunday, up from 39.8 million last year, AT&amp;T spokeswoman Judie Studt
said in Omaha.
   There were 46.8 million calls on Mother's Day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of television comedy's most familiar
fathers, Robert Young of ``Father Knows Best'' and Fred MacMurray of
``My Three Sons,'' were spending a low-key Father's Day on Sunday.
   Young, who as the venerable Jim Anderson of ``Father Knows Best''
regularly solved family crises within a half-hour from 1954 to 1963,
was spending the day at home with the family.
   ``I'm just enjoying living,'' the 82-year-old actor said.
   So is McMurray, 80, who was the patriarch in ``My Three Sons''
from 1960 to 1972.
   He spent all day Saturday preparing his secret-recipe chile, said
his wife, Jane.
   ``He's having a big family dinner and his daughters are coming
home,'' Mrs. MacMurray said.
   ``He made a big batch of his famous, homemade chili,'' she said.
``We usually have some left over for the Fourth of July.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunday was Father's Day times four for
a man whose wife gave birth to quadruplets.
   ``It's a wonderful blessing,'' attorney Frank Dunten, 39, said
the day after his 38-year-old wife, Jennifer, delivered a boy and
three girls at Blodgett Memorial Medical Center.
   The quadruplets were in good condition Sunday evening, said a
nursing supervisor who declined to give her name.
   The infants, ranging in weight from 3 pounds, 3 ounces to 3
pounds, 12 ounces, were named Jacqueline Lloyd, Jennifer Lloyd,
Katherine Lloyd and Daniel Lloyd. The middle name is for Mrs.
Dunten's father, who died last year.
   The couple have two other children, Jessica, 11, and Erica, 6.
They plan to move from their three-bedroom home in Cascade Township
to a six-bedroom home in East Grand Rapids.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of being $44,000 behind in
child-support payments and 22 other alleged ``deadbeat dads'' spent
Father's Day weekend behind bars, said an official with the district
attorney's office.
   The 23 were arrested Saturday in a roundup that has become an
annual event, according to Stan Trom, director of the district
attorney's child support division.
   Most of those arrested owed $6,000 to $7,000 and were at least
three months late with their payments, Trom said.
