<DOCNO> AP890618-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ArmsTalks     06-18 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Talks On Long-Range Nuclear Weapons To Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-Soviet talks on reducing long-range nuclear
weapons resume Monday after a seven-month break during which the
Bush administration reviewed the U.S. position during the presidency
of Ronald Reagan.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Friday the ``previous
administration left an excellent foundation on which to build. ...
There will be a considerable degree of continuity'' by the U.S.
negotiators.
   Yuri Nazarkin, the new leader of the Soviet delegation, indicated
upon arrival in Geneva that Moscow's fundamental positions also
remain unchanged.
   The new chief U.S. envoy is Richard Burt, former ambassador to
West Germany. He will lead the American delegation in the START
(Strategic Arms Reduction Talks) negotiations.
   The new round is expected to last about six weeks.
   Parallel to the START talks, the two sides also will reopen
negotiations on space and defense issues. Lem Masterkov continues as
the top Soviet negotiator in the START talks.
   U.S. officials said they will ask the Soviets to agree to try
methods for monitoring reductions of some long-range missiles. The
methods have been written into the draft of a proposed treaty.
   Neither side has indicated possible movement on three other
disputed areas _ U.S. plans for space-based missiles defenses, known
as the Star Wars plan; sea-launched cruise missiles, and how to deal
with mobile missiles.
   The Soviets oppose the Star Wars plan and want to limit
sea-launched cruise missiles.
   Burt has said a START treaty must ``fully protect our options for
developing and deploying'' missile defenses in space.
   Much of a draft treaty to cut each side's long-range (strategic)
nuclear forces by 30 to 50 percent has been accepted by both
delegations in the 10 previous rounds of the talks that began in
March 1985.
   The pact is intended to cover nuclear weapons that the two
superpowers could use to strike each other, including sea- and
land-based missiles as well as heavy bombers.
   Delegates are to begin by reviewing agreements already contained
in the 400-page draft text.
   The talks recessed Nov. 15 and were scheduled to reopen in
February but Bush ordered a delay for a reassessment of U.S.
policies. Secretary of State James Baker III and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev agreed last month on the resumption.
   Among the agreements reached in earlier rounds are lowered
ceilings of 6,000 nuclear warheads and 1,600 delivery vehicles _
missiles and bombers _ for each side. Outlines of a system for
monitoring compliance were also set.
</TEXT>
