<HEAD>Gov't Bans Top Moslem Groups; Three Arabs Slain; Jewish Settler Found
Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 21 graf to UPDATE with protest of death of Jewish
settler, army imposes curfew, new info. Pickup 21st graf `The meeting...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed two Arab
teen-agers Sunday and the body of a Jewish settler was found with a
knife in his chest and his pistol missing, sparking protests by
other settlers.
   In another attempt to quell the 18-month uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, the government outlawed three Moslem
fundamentalist organizations.
   The military command said the body of a Jewish settler was found
in a deserted area between the West Bank villages of Burkin and
Salfit by an Arab who notified Israeli soldiers. It said army units
rushed to the area, imposed a curfew on both villages and launching
a search for the killers.
   Army officials gave no further information and declined to say if
they suspected Arab terrorists.
   Angry settlers quickly held protest demonstrations.
   Israel radio said the victim was a 48-year-old resident of the
settlement of Ariel, 21 miles north of Jerusalem. The national Itim
news agency identified the settler as Friedrich Weisenfeld.
   Israel radio reported the slain man was found in his car, his
pistol was missing and an empty holster and binoculars were near the
body.
   In Ariel settlers drove their cars through the streets, honking
the horns, while their leaders gathered at the local council
building to consider protest actions.
   Dozens of settlers drove to Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin's
house in Tel Aviv and shouted ``Rabin, resign!''
   Police watched but did not intervene, according to Israel army
radio.
   Israeli said the army command, fearing vigilante actions by the
settlers, sent West Bank commander Brig. Gen. Gabi Ofir to Ariel.
   Arab reports said the two teen-agers slain by Israeli troops were
shot in the West Bank town of Nablus.
   The army said that in the Gaza Strip an Arab shot at an Israeli
officer, killing a crippled Palestinian vendor and slightly wounding
the officer.
   Eighteen Palestinians were wounded by Israli soldiers in seven
clashes in the occupied territories, according to Arab reporters.
   The Arab deaths brought to 524 the number of Palestinians killed
in the uprising that began in December 1987. Twenty-two Israelis
have been killed in violence related to the revolt.
   The Cabinet decided Sunday to outlaw the fundamentalist Hamas
movement and the extremist Hezbollah and Islamic Jihad groups. Hamas
and Islamic Jihad are the leading Moslem fundamentalist groups in
Gaza.
   Membership in the banned organizations could be punished by up to
10 years in prison.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, also operates in southern Lebanon. It
is believed to be the umbrella organization for the Lebanese Islamic
Jihad, or Islamic holy war, and other pro-Iranian groups holding
foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   The government has nurtured some Moslem fundamentalists as a
possible alternative to the Palestine Liberation Organization. But
the fundamentalists have adopted a stand calling for an Islamic
state in the region that would include Israel and the occupied
territories.
   In a May crackdown, more than 200 Hamas militants, including
spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, were arrested.
   Avigdor Feldman, an Israeli attorney specializing in security
cases, said the government decision ``immediately makes all contacts
with these groups illegal.''
   In Nablus, Saleh Salah Bahsh, 17, was fatally shot in the back
Sunday, hospital officials said.
   An army spokesman said the youth was stopped by soldiers and
asked to identify himself, and ``all of a sudden, he hit one of the
unit commanders and started fleeing on foot.'' Soldiers opened fire
when the youth refused to halt, he said.
   Hours later, Israeli soldiers dispersing a rock-throwing protest
shot in the head and killed 19-year-old Mahdi Jamus, Arab reports
and Israel radio said.
   In the Gaza Strip, a 45-year-old Palestinian was killed and an
Israeli officer was wounded outside a government office when an Arab
assailant in a car opened fire, according to Israeli and Arab
reports.
   The Palestinian, Salih Subeh Magadmeh, was rushed to Gaza's Shifa
hospital where he died. The army said Israel Ben-Ishai, the
reservist officer, was wounded in the shoulder.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's office confirmed plans to meet
Palestinians to discuss his proposal to hold elections in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The plan calls for negotiations
with elected Palestinian representatives on interim self-rule for
the 1.7 million residents of the territories.
   The meeting is to take place secretly next month in Jerusalem,
without publication of the participants' names to prevent any
reprisal by Palestinian militants opposed to talks, Shamir's
spokesman Avi Pazner said.
   The daily Haaretz newspaper quoted diplomatic sources in London
as saying PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat had given approval for 10
Palestinians to speak with Israeli officials. This came despite
objections from Farouk Kaddoumi, another senior PLO official, the
paper said.
</TEXT>
