<HEAD>Pepper's Brother Criticizes Niece for Announcing Candidacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Rep. Claude Pepper's brother
criticized their niece Sunday for joining the race for the House
seat her uncle held for 27 years.
   Retired broadcaster Frank Pepper, 71, said he learned about JoAnn
Pepper's campaign announcement in his morning newspaper.
   ``I was very surprised,'' he said. ``At no time was I ever
consulted about her plans, and it appears she has been talked into
something about which she knows very little.''
   Ms. Pepper said in Miami on Friday that she would seek the
Democratic nomination for the 18th District in the Aug. 1 election.
   The 38-year-old federal probation officer was the third announced
candidate for the party's nomination to succeed her uncle, who died
May 30 at age 88. Candidates have until Tuesday to enter the race.
   Ms. Pepper is the adopted daughter of the late Joseph Pepper,
brother to Frank and Claude. Claude Pepper left her $50,000 in his
will.
   ``She was very, very close to (Claude Pepper), like a daughter to
him, and she would like to continue with his work,'' Maria Tolon,
the late congressman's Hispanic liaison in Miami said earlier.
   Other candidates for the Democratic nomination are educator
Marvin Dunn and retired industrialist Bernard Anscher.
   Candidates for the Republican nomination are state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen, lawyer Jeff Allen and Carlos Perez, a businessman and
conservative activist.
