<HEAD>Record Number of Exhibitors, Visitors at Paris Air Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 38th Paris Air Show closed Sunday after hosting
a record number of visitors and exhibitors, organizers said.
   The 10-day show featured demonstration flights by more than 210
aircraft, press conferences attended by more than 2,000 journalists
and business deals amid luxurious hi-tech pavilions of 1,600
exhibitors.
   The biannual show started inauspiciously June 8 when a Soviet
MiG-29 fighter crashed executing a low flypass. Pilot Anatoly
Kvotchur directed the jet away from spectators and aircraft, and
ejected to safety.
   Among deals announced were the sale of 20 Super Puma helicopters
by the French Aerospatiale to Bristow Helicopter.
   The European consortium Airbus reported 22 orders for the A321
and seven A300-600R planes to Japan Systems.
   The air show recorded 103,768 entrances this year, a 20 percent
increase over a 1987 record.
