<HEAD>Evacuation Ordered when Fire-Warning Light Stays On</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, `The 91...,' to clarify that
jet was Piedmont flight with USAir markings.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FTL1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Piedmont airliner preparing for
takeoff with 97 people aboard was evacuated Sunday when a warning
light indicated an engine fire, airline officials said.
   No serious injuries were reported and there may not have been a
fire, said Larry Pickett, a spokesman for USAir, Piedmont's parent
company.
   The 91 passengers and six crew members fled the twin-engine
Boeing 737-200 bound for Tampa within minutes using emergency
chutes, Pickett said.
   The jet had USAir markings even though it was officially a
Piedmont flight, said Pickett, adding that the two carriers are in
the process of integrating their operations.
   The evacuation was ordered as the jetliner was preparing to taxi
out for takeoff around 1 p.m., the spokesman said. Engine No. 2 was
started without difficulty, but as No. 1 was started the fire
warning light came on.
   The pilot activated an extinguisher system, but the light stayed
on and the pilot ordered the evacuation, Pickett said.
   Passengers went to Tampa on other flights.
   Pickett said it was uncertain whether there was a fire or a
malfunction in the warning-light system.
