<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-18 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 4 Indian Troops, Extremists Kill 10 Sinhalese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels blew up an Indian army
truck in eastern Sri Lanka, killing four Indian soldiers and two
suspected rebels, Indian officials said Sunday. Ten Sinhalese were
reported killed in other weekend violence.
   Sri Lankan military officials said the separatist rebels exploded
the truck with a land mine Saturday in Batticaloa district, 136
miles east of Colombo.
   Two soldiers and eight suspected rebels arrested by the soldiers
were injured seriously in the blast, said officials who cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   An Indian High Commission spokeswoman, who also cannot be
identified, said the mine was planted by the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam.
   The Tamil Tigers currently are negotiating with President
Ranasinghe Premadasa's government to end their six-year war for a
separate nation that has claimed 9,000 lives.
   In the last two years, the war has expanded to include Indian
soldiers who came to Sri Lanka to disarm rebels. At least 800 Indian
troops have died. They were deployed to oversee a peace accord
signed by India and Sri Lanka in 1987.
   But the troops' presence, estimated at 45,000, was bitterly
opposed by hard-liners in the government and the extremist Sinhalese
People's Liberation Front.
   The front said the deployment compromised Sri Lanka's
independence and began another war in which they have killed at
least 3,500 people, mostly government officials and fellow Sinhalese.
   In their latest attack, the front killed 10 Sinhalese since
Saturday, police officials said on condition of anonymity. Seven
were fatally shot at Kuliyaitiya, 40 miles northeast of Colombo and
three in Galle district, 70 miles south of the capital, they said.
   Police said front militants also set fire to 15 state-owned buses
around Colombo.
   The front has called for a boycott of Indian goods and warned all
Indians to leave Sri Lanka by June 14 or risk death. But no violence
against Indians has been reported.
   Premadasa also has asked India to pull out its troops by July 29,
the second anniversary of the accord. But India says the troops will
withdraw only after local autonomy is devolved fully in the
northeast, where most of Sri Lanka's 2.8 million Tamils live. India
became involved in the ethnic strife because of political pressures
from its own 60 million Tamils.
   Tamils are an ethnic minority charging they are discriminated
against by Sri Lanka's majority Sinhalese, who constitute 75 percent
of the 16 million people.
</TEXT>
