<FIRST>u i AM-Europarliament 1stLd-Writethru a0716 06-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europarliament, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialists, Environmentalists, Extreme Right Post Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with preliminary figures showing
socialists and environmentalists scoring well. Pickup 13th graf `Recent
polls...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialists and environmentalists scored
big wins in European Parliament elections, according to vote
projections released early Monday a few hours after the last polls
closed.
   Preliminary results from all 12 countries of the European
Economic Community indicated the number of socialist deputies will
increase from 166 to 192 in the 518-seat body based in Strasbourg,
France.
   Although it is still mainly a consultative body, the Parliament
could play a major role in the trading bloc's efforts to forge a
single borderless market by late 1992.
   Voters in Belgium, West Germany, Greece, France, Luxembourg,
Italy and Portugal cast their ballots Sunday. Elections took place
Thursday in the other EEC nations _ Ireland, Britain, Denmark, Spain
and the Netherlands.
   Final results involving all 7,126 candidates from 178 national
political parties were not expected to be announced until late
Monday.
   Each country elected its own deputies to the Parliament.
   News media projections, preliminary EEC reports and exit polls
gave this partial indication of the composition of the new
legislatures:
   Greens and other environmentalist parties are among the
significant gainers after the socialists, winning 18 more seats for
a total 38.
   Communist parties were losing eight of their 48 seats, but an
alliance of socialists, environmentalists and communists would
control a majority with 270 deputies.
   Although many of the gains were made at the expense of
conservatives, extreme right-wing parties in France and West Germany
fared well. West Germany's Republican Party was expected to enter
the Parliament for the first time with seven seats. France's
National Front was holding on to its 10 seats.
   Projections showed British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservatives dropping from 45 seats to 26 while the opposition
Labor Party would increase its number of deputies from 32 to 51.
   The EEC, or Common Market, used a staggered system of reporting
results based on poll-closing times in the various countries.
Results of the balloting in Thursday's elections were withheld
pending the elections Sunday.
   Results were tabulated for all of Britain except Northern
Ireland. The returns from that British province were not to be
released until midday Monday along with the outcome of the election
in the republic of Ireland.
   The socialists, with 166 seats, were the largest political group
in the previous Parliament.
   The Parliament meets one week each month in Strasbourg.
   Recent polls have shown many of the 325 million people in the EEC
countries consider the Parliament to be little more than a debating
society, but reforms adopted in July 1987 give it more power.
   It can veto some EEC treaties with other countries, amend or
reject the annual budget, fire the 17-member Executive Commission
and delay an opinion on proposed laws, thus preventing them from
taking effect.
   The two other institutions involved in the community's lawmaking
process are the Executive Commission and Council of Ministers, which
are based in Brussels.
</TEXT>
