<FIRST>r a AM-HelicopterCrash     06-18 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Probe Massachusetts Helicopter Crash That Killed Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANDWICH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military investigators Sunday picked
through the far-flung wreckage of a helicopter that crashed in thick
fog, killing four National Guardsmen and two Army Reservists.
   The Army and the Delaware Army National Guard are conducting
parallel probes of the crash, said Lt. Col. Stuart Tauber, a
Massachusetts National Guard spokesman at Camp Edwards.
   The Bell UH-1 Huey crashed early Saturday in Yarmouth, a tourist
haven about 30 miles east of this Cape Cod town, while returning
from T.F. Greene Airport in Warwick, R.I.
   The helicopter cut a 20-foot wide path through the woods before
crashing, throwing its doors, glass and other debris more than 30
feet. Debris was found in a 150-foot radius around the impact site,
investigators said.
   The crew was halfway through a two-week training exercise at Camp
Edwards near this Cape Cod town. The exercise includes 495 members
of the Delaware guard.
   The last two victims were identified Sunday as Master Sgt. Robert
E. Lucey Jr. of Emporia, Va., and Spec. Samuel K. May of Richmond,
Va., of the Virginia Army Reserve, said Reserve Maj. Mari K. Eder.
   The other victims, previously identified, were Delaware National
Guardsmen Staff Sgt. Benjamin Robert Greenplate, 40, of Newark,
Del.; and 1st Lt. David Joseph Hendry, 26, and Chief Warrant Officer
Hugh Bryan Pearce, 35, both of Wilmington, Del.
   Pearce was the pilot, Hendry was the co-pilot and Greenplate was
the crew chief.
   Also killed was Connecticut National Guard Sgt. Ward Arthur
Cornell, 43, of Mansfield, Conn.
</TEXT>
