<HEAD>Union Membership Approves Contract With GE, Avoiding Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union workers at three General Electric Co.
plants in southern New Jersey unanimously approved a contract
Sunday, averting a threatened strike.
   Frank Ward, president of Local 241 of the International
Federation of Professional and Technical Engineers, said the
contract calls for an across-the-board 5 percent increase in wages
over three years. It also raises top pay levels an additional 2{
percent and provides merit raises of up to 4 percent each year, he
said.
   About 500 union members from plants in Camden, Moorestown and
Gibbsboro unanimously approved the contract on a voice vote, Ward
said.
   The current contract expired at 12:01 a.m. Friday, and union
members had planned to strike.
   The union represents 700 technical engineers, laboratory
personnel, writers and illustrators. The average salary is about
$25,000, Ward said.
