<HEAD>Investor Group May Attempt To Force Sale Of Chair Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group says it may buy or sell
stock or seek a merger or liquidation of La-Z-Boy Chair Co. to try
to increase the value of its stock.
   The Connecticut-based group, which holds 5.6 percent of
La-Z-Boy's shares, announced its intention in documents filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The group, made up of two partnerships _ Prescott Associates and
Idoya Partners _ may be trying to boost interest in the Monroe-based
company's stock but is unlikely to be able to force the company's
hand, said Elliott Schlang, an analyst who follows La-Z-Boy for
Prescott, Ball and Turben Inc. in Cleveland.
   La-Z-Boy's management owns a high enough percentage of the
company's stock to make it extremely unlikely for a hostile bidder
to be able to acquire a controlling interest or force a merger or
sale, Schlang said.
